# Feed Serving (getFeedSkeleton)

Read `docs/IMPLEMENTATION_SPEC.md` §9 for complete code patterns.

## Bluesky API Contract (EXACT)
- Endpoint: `GET /xrpc/app.bsky.feed.getFeedSkeleton`
- Query params: `feed` (AT-URI of this feed), `cursor` (optional string), `limit` (default 50, max 100)
- Response: `{ cursor?: string, feed: [{ post: "at://did/collection/rkey" }] }`
- Returns ONLY post URIs — Bluesky's AppView handles hydration
- Target response time: <50ms

## CRITICAL PERFORMANCE RULE
NEVER call external APIs in this handler. No Bluesky API, no ML inference, no network requests.
Read only from Redis (pre-computed rankings) and PostgreSQL (fallback).

## Cursor Strategy (Pagination Stability)
- First page request (no cursor): Create snapshot — generate random ID, cache ranked URIs in Redis sorted set with 5min TTL
- Subsequent pages: Read from snapshot at offset
- Cursor format: `base64url(JSON.stringify({ s: snapshotId, o: offset }))`
- If snapshot expired (TTL hit): return empty feed array (client will refresh from top)
- NEVER use live query offsets — rankings change between page loads

## Subscriber Tracking
- Extract requester DID from JWT `Authorization` header (if present)
- Upsert to `subscribers` table (fire-and-forget, don't block response)
- Feed is public — auth is optional, for tracking only

## Required Endpoints
1. `GET /xrpc/app.bsky.feed.getFeedSkeleton` — the feed itself
2. `GET /xrpc/app.bsky.feed.describeFeedGenerator` — feed metadata
3. `GET /.well-known/did.json` — DID document (for did:web resolution)
